<table-wrap position="float" id="tbl4">
 <label>Table 4</label>
 <caption>
  <p>Differences Between Positive and Negative Pressure Areas</p>
 </caption>
 <table frame="hsides" rules="groups">
  <thead>
   <tr>
    <th>Engineering Characteristic</th>
    <th>Positive Pressure Areas (eg, PE)</th>
    <th>Negative Pressure Areas (eg, AII)</th>
   </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
   <tr>
    <td>Pressure differential</td>
    <td>&gt; +2.5 Pa (0.01-in. water gauge)</td>
    <td>&gt; −2.5 Pa (0.01-in. water gauge)</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td>Air changes per hour</td>
    <td>&gt;12</td>
    <td>≥12 (for renovation or new construction)</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td>Filtration efficiency</td>
    <td/>
    <td/>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td/>
    <td>Supply: 99.97% at 0.3 μm DOP</td>
    <td>Supply: 90% (dust spot test)</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td/>
    <td>Return: none required (if patient requires both PE and AII, return air should be HEPA-filtered or otherwise exhausted to outside)</td>
    <td>Return: 99.97% at 0.3 μm DOP (HEPA filtration of exhaust air from AII rooms should not be required, provided exhaust has been properly located to prevent re-entry into building)</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td>Room airflow direction</td>
    <td>Out to adjacent area</td>
    <td>In to room</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td>Clean-to-dirty airflow in room</td>
    <td>Away from patient (high-risk patient, immunosuppressed patient)</td>
    <td>Toward patient (airborne disease patient)</td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td>Ideal pressure differential
     <xref rid="bib40" ref-type="bibr">
      <sup>40</sup>
     </xref>
    </td>
    <td>&gt; +8 Pa</td>
    <td>&gt; −2.5 Pa</td>
   </tr>
  </tbody>
 </table>
